---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="How Ureview picks arxiv math papers and generates a long-form AI reading of each one."
  activeNav="about"
>
  <div class="container">
    <section class="page-intro page-intro--prose">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </nav>
      <span class="page-intro-eyebrow">Masthead · Colophon</span>
      <h1 class="page-intro-title">About the gazette.</h1>
      <p class="page-intro-lede">
        A reading surface for trending arxiv math papers. Each paper gets
        one long-form machine reading of the proof, filed alongside the
        author's own abstract.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="essay-shell">
    <article class="essay">
      <section class="essay-disclaimers">
        <span class="essay-kicker">Key disclaimers</span>
        <ul>
          <li>Reviews are single-pass language-model readings, not peer review.</li>
          <li>The only human-uploaded field is <code>ai_proof_review</code> — the long-form prose itself. Everything else (title, authors, abstract, categories) is straight from arxiv.</li>
          <li>The abstract is the author's own arxiv abstract, verbatim.</li>
          <li>The queue is driven by the Hugging Face Daily Papers feed, filtered to <code>math.*</code> categories. No editorial calendar.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <h2 id="what-this-is">What this is</h2>
      <p>
        Ureview is an experimental reading surface for trending arxiv math papers.
        For every paper we surface the arxiv abstract and a long-form AI reading of
        the proof — what the paper shows, where the argument leans, what a careful
        reader should watch for.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how-it-works">How the data flows</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Papers are picked from <strong>Hugging Face Daily Papers</strong> as they surface, filtered to <code>math.*</code> arxiv categories.</li>
        <li>For each paper, the arxiv abstract is stored verbatim alongside the title, authors, and category list.</li>
        <li>A language model produces one long-form prose reading of the proof. That prose is the only human-uploaded field; nothing is parsed into scores or sub-fields.</li>
        <li>The pair is published as JSON to Cloudflare R2 and rendered into the review page.</li>
        <li>One review per paper. If the paper trends again later, we don't re-review it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="limits">What this isn't</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Not peer review, not an editorial endorsement, not a publication decision.</li>
        <li>Single-pass model output with no human verification.</li>
        <li>No author rebuttal flow — the arxiv link is one click away.</li>
        <li>Not a rating system. There are no scores, dimensions, or verdicts to compare across papers — only prose.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked</h2>

      <h3>Why no scores or ratings?</h3>
      <p>
        An earlier version of the site had a four-dimension rubric and a verdict leaning.
        Both were collapsed back into prose: scoring a proof on a 1–4 scale invited
        false precision, and the verdict label hid the reasoning that produced it.
        The long-form reading carries the same judgement, but the reader has to read it.
      </p>

      <h3>Is this peer review?</h3>
      <p>No. It is a lightweight AI reading aid. Use the source link to check the paper yourself.</p>

      <h3>How are papers picked?</h3>
      <p>
        We watch the Hugging Face Daily Papers feed and keep only the <code>math.*</code>
        entries we haven't read yet. No fixed daily quota, no editorial calendar — the
        feed ebbs and flows with what HF curates.
      </p>

      <h3>Why was this paper selected?</h3>
      <p>
        Because it surfaced on Hugging Face Daily Papers, has an arxiv math category,
        and we hadn't read it yet. There is no venue-specific editorial selection.
      </p>

      <h3>Can the review be wrong?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Treat the reading as a first-pass impression. The abstract and the arxiv
        link are always one click away — read the paper yourself if it matters.
      </p>

      <h2 id="colophon">Colophon</h2>
      <p>
        Set in <em>Fraunces</em> (variable serif, opsz + SOFT axes) and
        <em>IBM Plex Mono</em>. Published as static HTML from
        <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a>;
        review JSON hosted on Cloudflare R2.
        Math is rendered with <a href="https://katex.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KaTeX</a>.
        Hand-written CSS; no client framework.
      </p>
    </article>

    <aside class="essay-toc" aria-label="On this page">
      <span class="essay-toc-label">On this page</span>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#what-this-is">What this is</a></li>
        <li><a href="#how-it-works">How the data flows</a></li>
        <li><a href="#limits">What this isn't</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq">Frequently asked</a></li>
        <li><a href="#colophon">Colophon</a></li>
      </ol>
    </aside>
  </div>
</Layout>
